sub_title: Project Manager || Nepali Yuwa in Climate Action and Green Growth
summary:
An environmental and sustainability enthusiast working with youth and young professionals in the sector of DRR and Climate to promote data-driven decision-making. Joined since the inception phase, have led Climate and DRR Fellowship and created a pool of young professionals experienced in local DRR governance.   
I have a bachelor’s degree in Environmental Science and Mathematics from Hollins University, Virginia, USA. While completing her bachelor’s degree, I did a semester abroad in Cambodia where I lived with communities whose livelihoods were highly vulnerable to climate change and disaster. This experience ignited my interest in environmental research and sustainability and led her path to the Netherlands where I completed her master’s degree in Sustainability Science and Policy. This journey further extended to Uganda where I carried my thesis research exploring the sustainability initiative from the producing countries in the South through the case study of the Uganda Coffee Platform.

projects: [{'title': 'A Baseline Study of Fish Abundance and Species Richness of the Boeung Chuk Lake in Banteay Srei District in Siem Reap Province, Cambodia (Research Advisor: Dr. Megan English)', 'date': {'start': {'month': 4, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}, 'end': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2019}}, 'description': 'We conducted a baseline study of fish abundance and species richness with a focus on variation in diurnal and nocturnal fish catch at Boeung Chuk lake in Banteay Srei district in Siem Reap province. Fish were caught using 2.5 cm and 3.5 cm mesh gill nets in the morning and evening from April 17 to April 28, 2017. Along with our samples, seven interviews were conducted with local fishing families on species they had caught in the lake to compile a list of taxonomic information in addition to the species we caught. ', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Goma', 'last_name': 'Karki', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Project Manager || Nepali Yuwa in Climate Action and Green Growth'}]}, {'title': 'Fruit flies in California: Are they established or do detections represent new introductions? (Research Advisors: Dr. Jean Fallon, Dr. Daniel Derringer and Dr. Jonathan Walter)', 'date': {'start': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}, 'end': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2017}}, 'description': 'Here we used detection data of four species of fruit flies (medfly, Mexican fruit fly, guava fruit fly, and oriental fruit fly) in California and analyzed those data to examine whether these fruit flies’ species were established in California, or the detections represented new introductions. Factors influencing where and when insect pest invasions occur include; climate; human activities such as trade, migration, and transportation; and natural dispersal by the organism. To evaluate effects of these factors, we applied a set generalized additive models (GAMS) analogous to logistic regression to detection data for each species. We examined three different models: space-only, time-only and time and space to study detection nature of fruit flies. We evaluated the space-only and time-only model to isolate spatial and temporal patterns. ', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Goma', 'last_name': 'Karki', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Project Manager || Nepali Yuwa in Climate Action and Green Growth'}]}, {'title': 'Carbon Emissions and Coast of Standard Housing Vs. The Youth CAN focuses on working with young people, and empowering and providing them a platform to aid towards the post-COVID recovery and development process. Furthermore, the activities under Climate Fellowship, Climate Smart Entrepreneurship, Mentee-mentorship, Digital Advocacy, and Youth Sounding Board work towards empowering young people, providing them employment opportunities, generating innovative ideas to address climate and environmental issues, and advocating for policy changes to promote environmental protection.
